Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees.

In a #small pot{}, combine @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup}, 3/4 cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4), and @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in Step 5.

While rice cooks, wash and dry produce.

Trim and discard bottom 1 inch from @Asparagus{6%ounce}. Roughly chop @Parsley{1/4%ounce}. Zest and quarter @Lemon{1}.

== Sauce ==

In a #small bowl{}, combine @Sour Cream{3%tablespoon} and 1 tsp Old Bay Seasoning (2 tsp for 4 servings). Add water 1 tsp at a time until sauce reaches a drizzling consistency.

Place @Butter{2%tablespoon} in a #medium microwave-safe bowl{}. Microwave until melted, ~{30%seconds}.

Let cool slightly, then stir in @Panko Breadcrumbs{1/4%cup} and 1 tsp Old Bay Seasoning (2 tsp for 4). (Be sure to measure the Old Bay Seasoning—we sent more!)

== Cobia and Asparagus ==

Toss asparagus on one side of a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{2%teaspoon}, @salt{} and @pepper{} (for 4 servings, spread out across entire sheet).

Lightly oil empty side of baking sheet (for 4, use a second baking sheet). Pat @Cobia{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season with salt and pepper.

Place cobia on oiled side of sheet; brush tops with a thin layer of sauce (save the rest for serving). Mound with panko mixture, pressing firmly to adhere (no need to coat the undersides).

Roast on top rack (for 4, roast asparagus on top rack and cobia on middle rack) until crust is golden brown and fish is cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in parsley, lemon zest, @Butter{1%tablespoon}, and a squeeze of lemon juice until combined. Season with salt and pepper.

== To Serve ==

Divide cobia, rice, and asparagus between plates. Drizzle remaining sauce over cobia and serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Cobia is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.